WEBVTT

00:03.657 --> 00:05.625
Harvard trivia,
the lightning round.

00:05.692 --> 00:06.826
Go.

00:06.894 --> 00:08.261
Pulitzer Prizes.
46.

00:08.328 --> 00:10.012
- Nobel Peace Prizes.
- Five.

00:10.080 --> 00:12.113
What is the oldest book in
the Harvard library collection?

00:12.181 --> 00:13.444
- The Bible.
- Wrong.

00:13.511 --> 00:14.745
The Gutenberg Bible.

00:14.813 --> 00:16.386
Everyone knows
it's the Gutenberg Bible.

00:16.454 --> 00:17.618
Yes, but you didn't say it.

00:17.686 --> 00:19.720
The rules dictate
you must be precise,

00:19.787 --> 00:21.221
as the law is
a very precise endeavor.

00:22.620 --> 00:24.154
- How many U.S. Pr--
- Eight.

00:24.222 --> 00:25.820
That's not fair, you didn't
even finish the question.

00:25.888 --> 00:27.721
And yet it's right.
The question was gonna be

00:27.789 --> 00:29.556
"How many U.S. Presidents
attended Harvard?"

00:29.623 --> 00:31.494
- You want names?
- No, we get it.

00:31.561 --> 00:34.866
Final round.
Ross ahead by one.

00:34.934 --> 00:37.440
One question each.
Points are double.

00:37.508 --> 00:39.609
Double 'cause he wants
to keep you in the game, Seth.

00:39.677 --> 00:41.445
Bring it on, Ross.
I bleed crimson.

00:41.513 --> 00:43.915
Oh, venomous banter.
This is adorable, I love it.

00:43.983 --> 00:46.786
Ross, square pizza.
Where do you get it?

00:49.523 --> 00:50.589
Are you kidding?

00:50.657 --> 00:52.291
Any self-respecting
Harvard alumnus

00:52.358 --> 00:54.159
would know the answer
to that.

00:54.226 --> 00:55.860
Late night studying
and you want square pizza,

00:55.927 --> 00:57.195
where do you go?

00:57.262 --> 00:59.630
Um...

00:59.697 --> 01:01.198
You know,
I'm more of a burger guy.

01:01.266 --> 01:04.000
I study better on protein.

01:06.536 --> 01:08.604
I mean, that's just...
pathetic.

01:08.672 --> 01:09.738
It's Pinocchio's.

01:09.806 --> 01:11.675
Mm, I answer mine, I win.

01:11.743 --> 01:13.110
Yeah, I know.

01:16.450 --> 01:18.085
How many current
U.S. Supreme Court Justices

01:18.153 --> 01:19.486
are from our Alma Mater?

01:19.554 --> 01:22.390
Everybody knows that.

01:22.458 --> 01:23.692
Five.

01:23.760 --> 01:25.695
Hah! See, I told you
Keller was better.

01:25.762 --> 01:27.196
You owe me 20.

01:27.264 --> 01:28.699
- Awesome.
- Got anything to say, Ross?

01:28.766 --> 01:31.334
Nope.
Just that the answer's wrong.

01:31.402 --> 01:34.404
Scalia, Roberts,
Kennedy, Breyer, Kagan.

01:34.471 --> 01:35.872
- Ginsberg.
- Ruth Bader Ginsberg

01:35.939 --> 01:38.707
went to Columbia.
She graduated from Columbia,

01:38.775 --> 01:40.742
after she attended Harvard
for two years.

01:40.810 --> 01:42.344
The question was phrased

01:42.412 --> 01:44.412
"How many justices were
from Harvard?"

01:44.480 --> 01:46.280
Well, she was on
the <i>Harvard Law Review.</i>

01:46.348 --> 01:48.282
And when she arrived
at Columbia as a transfer,

01:48.350 --> 01:49.683
she was from Harvard.

01:49.751 --> 01:52.553
The rules dictate
that you must be precise,

01:52.621 --> 01:55.257
as the law is
a precise endeavor.

01:55.325 --> 01:57.125
Told you Ross was hot.

02:01.966 --> 02:03.266
Congratulations.

02:03.334 --> 02:05.534
This is what you get
for second place.

02:05.602 --> 02:08.705
To the victor belongs
the spoils.

02:08.773 --> 02:11.576
A case.
Pro bono, one of your very own.

02:13.312 --> 02:14.345
Congratulations, enjoy.

02:16.000 --> 02:22.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

02:24.192 --> 02:26.594
Louis knows.

02:26.662 --> 02:28.930
- Louis knows what?
- My dirty little secret.

02:28.998 --> 02:30.398
- You're Canadian?
- Ha, ha, ha, ha.

02:30.466 --> 02:31.867
No, he knows that
I didn't go to Harvard.

02:31.935 --> 02:33.302
No, he doesn't.

02:33.369 --> 02:34.636
How can you
be so sure about that?

02:34.704 --> 02:36.004
Because you're walking
with me right now.

02:36.072 --> 02:37.739
He did this whole
Harvard trivia thing,

02:37.807 --> 02:38.740
and then he brought up
this pizza--

02:38.808 --> 02:40.309
Doesn't mean he knows.

02:40.376 --> 02:41.776
Look,
I think we need to hack

02:41.844 --> 02:42.911
into Harvard's system
or something.

02:42.979 --> 02:44.913
You know, put my records in.

02:44.981 --> 02:46.181
I can't,
I'm booked this weekend.

02:46.248 --> 02:48.116
I'm breaking into Fort Knox.

02:48.184 --> 02:50.051
I gotta return
some stolen doubloons.

02:50.119 --> 02:52.187
Okay, hilarious.
I'm serious.

02:52.255 --> 02:54.523
Listen, nobody's
gonna check into your past

02:54.591 --> 02:57.026
unless you
give them reason to.

02:57.094 --> 03:00.130
Louis is devious,
but he's not bold.

03:00.198 --> 03:01.932
He won't think we did this.

03:02.000 --> 03:04.035
Because he'd never
think to do it himself.

03:04.102 --> 03:06.437
Doubloons?

03:06.505 --> 03:08.239
The ridiculousness of
your suggestion

03:08.307 --> 03:09.408
warranted the use of
a silly word.

03:09.475 --> 03:11.543
Got it.

03:24.460 --> 03:25.927
Was that Quentin Sainz
I just saw leaving?

03:25.995 --> 03:27.195
Mm-hmm.
You know him?

03:27.263 --> 03:28.997
I know of him.

03:29.064 --> 03:31.033
Why was he holding your hands?
Kissing them?

03:31.100 --> 03:32.668
What are
you implying, Harvey?

03:32.735 --> 03:34.369
I don't know, maybe
you two are going steady.

03:34.437 --> 03:37.106
I was implying
that it looked like

03:37.173 --> 03:39.141
he was grateful to you
for taking his case.

03:39.209 --> 03:41.277
Good, 'cause that's
exactly what it was.

03:41.345 --> 03:43.313
That's a bad move.
We may make money

03:43.380 --> 03:45.381
billing out on their defense,
but when we lose--

03:45.449 --> 03:47.684
which we will--it's gonna
hurt us in the long run.

03:47.752 --> 03:51.020
- How do you know we'll lose?
- Because it's my job to know.

03:51.088 --> 03:53.456
And his company's A.L.S.
wonder drug is killing people.

03:53.524 --> 03:56.026
A.L.S. is incurable.

03:56.094 --> 03:57.761
And everyone
who is taking that drug

03:57.828 --> 03:59.396
is going to die anyway.

03:59.463 --> 04:02.132
Hm.
That's your defense?

04:02.199 --> 04:04.734
If he kills them a little
faster, it's a public service?

04:04.802 --> 04:08.905
Our defense is
those allegations are untrue.

04:08.973 --> 04:10.474
He has taken
this story all over town,

04:10.542 --> 04:12.409
and not a single firm thinks
he has a case.

04:12.477 --> 04:14.011
Which is why he came to me.

04:14.079 --> 04:15.880
Because he wants someone
who believes in him.

04:15.948 --> 04:18.416
And what is it exactly
that makes you believe in him?

04:18.483 --> 04:20.218
Well, I got to know
his character pretty well

04:20.286 --> 04:21.420
during the time
that we were married.

04:25.025 --> 04:27.487
Quentin is
expecting you tomorrow.

